    name='search',
    response={
      'result': """CVE-2025-55182, also known as "React2Shell," is a critical unauthenticated Remote Code Execution (RCE) vulnerability with a CVSS score of 10.0. It significantly impacts React Server Components, Next.js, and other related frameworks that utilize the `react-server` package and the React Server Components (RSC) "Flight" protocol.

The core of this vulnerability lies in insecure deserialization and inadequate validation of incoming payloads in affected React Server Components versions. This flaw enables attackers to inject malicious structures, resulting in **server-side prototype pollution**. Through this prototype pollution, attackers can then trigger a "gadget chain" that leads to arbitrary code execution on the vulnerable server.

Exploitation of CVE-2025-55182 involves sending a specially crafted HTTP POST request that contains a serialized object. When the server processes and deserializes this malicious input, it executes the attacker's code within the NodeJS runtime. A key concern is that default configurations of affected applications are vulnerable, meaning no special setup or developer error is required for exploitation. Publicly available proof-of-concept exploits have made this vulnerability readily exploitable.

The impact of successful exploitation is severe, granting attackers the ability to execute arbitrary commands on compromised servers, including establishing reverse shells. Exploitation activity related to this CVE was detected as early as December 5, 2025, with organizations urged to patch vulnerable instances immediately. As a temporary mitigation measure, deploying Web Application Firewall (WAF) rules can help detect and block exploitation attempts."""
    }
  )
)] role='user'
